04347nam a22005535i 9780231557177DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315571777 a10.7312/powe207902doi  a(DE-B1597)665684  a(OCoLC)1377549322  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN4731b.P694 2023 7aLAN0080002bisacsh04a070.4223  aAP 294002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/7266:6581 aPowers, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Journalist's Predicament :bDifficult Choices in a Declining Profession /cSandra Vera-Zambrano, Matthew Powers. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION Why Would Anyone Be a Journalist? -- tCHAPTER ONE The Genesis of the Journalist’s Predicament -- tCHAPTER TWO Living For— and Maybe Off— Journalism -- tCHAPTER THREE At Their Best -- tCHAPTER FOUR Conserve, Challenge, Accede -- tCHAPTER FIVE Leaving Journalism -- tEPILOGUE Is Journalism Dying? -- tAppendix A: Interviewing as Comprehension -- tAppendix B: Seattle and Toulouse as Regional Media -- tAppendix C: Tables and Data -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLow pay. Uncertain work prospects. Diminished prestige. Why would anyone still want be a journalist? Drawing on in-depth interviews in France and the United States, Matthew Powers and Sandra Vera-Zambrano explore the ways individuals come to believe that journalism is a worthy pursuit—and how that conviction is managed and sometimes dissolves amid the profession’s ongoing upheavals.For many people, journalism represents a job that is interesting and substantial, with opportunities for expression, a sense of self-fulfillment, and a connection to broader social values. By distilling complex ideas, holding the powerful to account, and revealing hidden realities, journalists play a crucial role in helping audiences make sense of the world. Experiences in the profession, though, are often far more disappointing. Many find themselves doing tasks that bear little relation to what attracted them initially or are frustrated by institutions privileging what sells over what informs. The imbalance between the profession’s economic woes and its social importance threatens to erode individuals’ beliefs that journalism remains a worthwhile pursuit. Powers and Vera-Zambrano emphasize that, as with many seemingly individual choices, social factors—class, gender, education, and race—shape how journalists make sense of their profession and whether or not they remain in it.An in-depth story of one profession under pressure, The Journalist’s Predicament uncovers tensions that also confront other socially important jobs like teaching, nursing, and caretaking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJournalism. 0aJournalistsxAttitudes. 0aJournalistsxJob stress. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Journalism.2bisacsh1 aVera-Zambrano, Sandra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967040uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/powe2079040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231557177423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231557177/original  a978-3-11-074967-0  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles